@node "Purpose" "Purpose"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Disclaimer"
 If you use Music-X and  have   ARexx    and  the  RexxEdit  module you will
be already familiar with the extra functions that  these macros provide.

For those who are not familiar with what the Music-X ARexx macros are or do
then here's a brief explanation..

The commercial  release of the upgraded  Music-X  V2.0 came bundled  with 5
ARexx macros

  1.CopyTranspose, 2. InterpolateSlope, 3. TimeStretcher, 4.TrimEnd
  and 5. V-Scaler.

There was supposed to be an Ear Trainer macro but this never appeared?

Anyway,  the  ARexx  macros  were  produced  with  the  view  of  providing
additional tools for editing MIDI  data  within the Music-X MIDI Sequencing
software environment.. Although Music-X has an excellent wide range of tool
facilities for editing MIDI  data  within  the  software  itself the  ARexx
macro additions makes certain editing of MIDI data, previously difficult or
out-of-reach, that much easier now  by  the  emergence  of new ARexx macros
produced by Music-X users themselves.

The original distribution of the  5  ARexx  macros  above, together with an
ARexx Music-X Performance filer player and RexxEDIT module and accompanying
documentation could be located on  INTERNET  and  later the AMINET archives
and  CD-ROMs.  At  a   later  date  MicroIllusions/Hollyware  Entertainment
upgraded Music-X from V1.1 to V2.0 which  now came bundled with the 5 ARexx
macros and were fully documented in the Addendum part of the user manual..

For  a  more  indepth  read  of    the   @{"REXXEDIT" link "REXXEDIT" 0} documentation then this
has also been included within this package..

The macros contained here within this package were developed from the ideas
contained within the original 5 ARexx  macros  which came with Music-X V2.0
but have further expanded the editing  options  for a wider variety of MIDI
data within the Music-X V2.0 MIDI Sequencing software.
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Purpose"


Any Amiga with the Music-X V2.0 MIDI Sequencing software

Kickstart 2.0 or higher (version 37.175 preferred)

RexxMast, accompanying ARexx libraries and commands

RexxEdit

The Music-X ARexx macros have been  tested  on an A2000 HD with Commodore's
A2091 SCSI Controller, a  Quantum  Fireball 540Mb internal SCSI  harddrive,
a A2630/68030  Accelerator 5Mb  RAM, a  Quantum  Lightning  730Mb  external
SCSI harddrive running both Workbench 2.1 and 3.0..

Please don't hesitate to contact me in case of any problems with any of the
Music-X ARexx macros on your system  I'll  be  glad to correct any problems
and send you a revised version  of  a  particular  ARexx  macro  as long as
you include a  jiffy bag and return  postage along with  the  macro  and an
explanation in an ASCII doc on a blank Amiga formatted disk..
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Macro Descriptions"
@prev "Requirements"

 Installation

In order to gain the best use  of  these Music-X ARexx macros then you will
need to install them in the  relevant rexx sub-directory within the Music-X
directory on your harddrive or   the   rexx   directory  on the Music-X 2.0
floppy disk.. Obviously, they  will  work  more  efficiently on a harddrive
system with a 68020 or above accelerator and with more than 1Mb of RAM, but
they should work from floppy,  particularly  if you powerpack (crunch) some
of  the  files  on  the  floppy   disk   to  make  room  for  the  macros..
Additionally, the REXXMAST, which comes bundled  with the ARexx language on
Workbench 2.04 and Workbench 3.0  etc.,  needs  to  be installed along with
some additional files and libraries in order that these ARexx macros will
run..

If you possess Music-X V2.0, then the manual provides information regarding
setting up ARexx on an  Amiga  system  for  the  ARexx macros purposes..

See @{"Setting up ARexx" link "SettingUpARexx" 0}  which contains detailed instructions of how to set up
ARexx for the Music-X macros included in this package..
@endnode

